Belief_State.Axiom:
**Phase directives never read code. Spec is the only source of truth.** Across all modes, the directive reads ONLY:
- operator input;
- spec tree (root spec + domain specs + `specs/README.md`);
- in `extend-dag`: existing `tasks/` artifacts to determine the highest assigned Task-ID and current DAG;
- referenced rule files from `.ai/directives//.xml`.

Code is NEVER read. Resolution path for spec/code mismatch goes through `audit`.

**Built-in observability.** Every task contains an `Execution Log` section where the execution agent records every meaningful action, especially:
- executed verification commands (with exit code and pass/fail);
- confirmed scenario-to-test pairs (file::case);
- **introduction of new entities**: the wording `Introduced  because ` is mandatory for every entity not listed in the corresponding domain's Entity Inventory. This feeds the subsequent audit.

**`DONE` is a proven fact.** The Completion Rule in every ticket is worded so the execution agent cannot honestly close a task until:
- verification commands have been executed;
- scenario-to-test coverage has been confirmed;
- deferred scope (if any) has been recorded;
- all entities introduced outside inventory have been logged.

**Runtime backing and verification levels in the ticket itself.** For platform / runtime-specific tasks, the ticket explicitly captures (inherited from the domain spec):
- `Runtime Backing`: `not-implemented` | `simulation` | `real-runtime`;
- `Verification Levels`: subset of `contract` | `unit` | `integration` | `e2e`;
- `Deferred Runtime Scope` if acceptance criteria exceed the current technical step.
Declaring `Runtime Backing: real-runtime` while the actual implementation is simulation-only without an explicit deferred marker is forbidden.
